Welcome 

Hello, and welcome here exactly as you are.
My name is Irene. I am a nurse specialised in mental health, hypnotherapist, and wellbeing coach supporting people living with Functional Neurological Disorder (FND).
From early in my studies and professional journey, I became curious about practices that help the body and mind work together to improve well-being, support nervous system regulation, and create a nicer experience of life. 
As a nurse, I have worked in NHS mental health hospitals, neurology, and at a neuropsychiatric ward, a specialized inpatient ward for people living with FND. It was there that I first encountered FND and witnessed the many challenges it can bring to every area of life. My experience working in this ward inspired me to dedicate my professional practice to supporting people living with FND.
Since then, I have been running courses in collaboration with FND charities, both online and in person, and I have had the opportunity to meet hundreds of people living with FND around the world. Through these courses and 1:1 sessions, I have seen how techniques and practices, such as those grounded in mindfulness and nervous system regulation, can genuinely help people manage symptoms, feel better and improve their quality of life.
This book is the result of years of learning, noticing, listening, and collaborating. It brings together practices that have proven helpful in my work, alongside the voices of people living with  FND who share their own experiences. 
While it offers many supportive ideas and practices, it does not cover them all. I encourage you to stay curious and open, keep exploring, and discover what works best for you in managing symptoms and improving well-being.
Something I always like to remind people is that we are all different. What works for one person might not work for another. That is why I encourage you to choose the techniques that resonate with you and that you find helpful. Your journey is unique, and so is your toolkit.
My intention is not to offer a ‘quick fix’ or unrealistic promises, but to share practical tools, hopeful perspectives, and the wisdom of the lived experiences of the FND community. I hope this book can be a gentle companion and a source of support for people living with FND, as well as for their families, carers, professionals, and anyone else who may benefit.

It also feels important to me that this book gives something back to the community, which is why 50% of the profits will be donated to charities supporting people living with FND around the world.


About FND

Functional Neurological Disorder (FND) affects millions of children and adults worldwide and causes a wide range of symptoms, including movement difficulties, functional seizures, sensory changes, problems with thinking or memory, and more. Unlike conditions caused by structural damage to the nervous system, current understanding of FND suggests that it arises from changes in how the brain functions, processes signals, and coordinates communication within the body.
FND is one of the most common reasons people see a neurologist, second only to headaches. Yet it is still poorly understood by many professionals, stigmatized, and severely lacking in resources, treatment pathways, and consistent care worldwide.
While some people with FND are able to access treatment and support, many others around the world are still left without the care they need and deserve. It is very important, and deeply needed, that this changes. FND is real, as real as any other medical condition, and it needs to be seen and treated as such.
If you are curious to learn more, whether you are newly diagnosed, a family member, a carer, a professional, or anyone else, I hope you take the time to explore further, especially if you are a health professional. Raising awareness of FND is essential and urgently needed.

About this book

What is it?

This book is a guide that aims to promote a nicer experience with the body and mind.
It is a collection of:
Techniques gathered by me and by people living with FND, including practices drawn from approaches such as mindfulness, CBT, DBT, polyvagal theory, etc.
Shared voices from people living with FND,
Practices that are relatable and relevant to you and me (from people living with FND to everyone else).
It is simple and direct, easy to read and accessible.

It is a reminder of hope and connectedness, a reminder that you are not alone.

How was it made?

The book was created by gathering practices and techniques I have learned over the past years: studying, working in neurology, mental health and neuropsychiatric wards, running online courses, and supporting people living with FND through specialized programs and 1:1 sessions. 
It also includes answers collected through a survey shared with people living with FND in the UK, America and Spain. In this survey, participants were invited to share techniques related to the different topics presented in this book, along with messages they wished to pass on to others living with FND.
The organisation of information, the analysis of the survey’s data, and aspects of content drafting were supported through the use of AI tools.

How to use it?
This book is yours to use however you want. And however you want is however you want.
You may choose to open it at a random page, or you may prefer to read it from beginning to end. However you use it, I invite you to experience it in your own way, take what helps, add it to your toolkit, and return to it whenever you need.

What will you find inside?
Inside this book you will find 10 chapters, each focused on a specific topic: Breath, Senses, Pacing, Thoughts, Movement, Art, Social, Nutrition, Nature, and Compassion.
Each chapter contains five main practices, followed by reflections from people living with FND, sharing their experiences with these or similar techniques. All quotes in italics throughout the book come directly from those with lived experience of FND and are copied verbatim from the survey.
At the end of every chapter, you will also find extra practices shared by the community, marked with the symbol:
At the end of the book, you will find a dedicated space to write down the techniques that have helped or inspired you. You can use it as your personal reference guide, something you can return to whenever you need support or a reminder of what has worked for you.
You will also find a list of resources shared in the survey by people living with FND, along with a list of contributors and reviewers, including people with lived experience of FND and healthcare professionals.

 


BREATH

Breathing is a powerful tool. When we focus on our breath, we can calm our minds, reduce stress, and improve our overall well-being. 



“To my FND warriors. I know we feel alone and isolated and every day is a constant battle. But just remember you are loved! Keep going, keep being you and always remember to be kind to yourself and take it one day at a time. Please never give up! You got this! “

BOX BREATHING

Also known as square breathing, it is a technique to focus the mind and regulate breathing. It involves using a square shape as a guide for your breath.
How:
Visualize a square: each side is one phase.
Inhale for 4 counts (trace side 1).
Hold for 4 counts (side 2).
Exhale for 4 counts (side 3).
Pause for 4 counts (side 4).
Variations:
Triangle breathing: Use a triangle instead. Inhale, hold, exhale (each side 4 sec).
Custom shape: Pick any shape and use it to guide your breath.
Reflections:

“I use box breathing and conscious, controlled yoga breath work. They help to slow down my breathing, regulate my nervous system, release stress and bring me to a place of peace and calm.”
“Box breathing—use most days to calm the mind, shift the nervous system from fight/flight back to a state of calm, manage pain surges.”
COUNTING BREATHS

Counting breaths involves using specific patterns to regulate your breathing.

How:
Inhale. Breathe in through your nose for a count of 4 seconds.
Hold. Hold your breath for a count of 2 seconds.
Exhale. Breathe out through your mouth for a count of 6 seconds.
Tips:
Adjust the breath counts to what feels best for you. Longer inhalations can help energize and activate, while longer exhalations can soothe and relax.
Reflections:
“I breathe in for 4 seconds and out for 5 seconds. Focusing on the breath as I inhale and exhale helps me to focus and calm my body and mind when I am being triggered by something I cannot control.”

“If I feel a functional seizure coming, focusing on my breath, deep breath in, even longer breath out, can help me get more focused on my body. Sometimes this will stop the seizures from continuing and sometimes it gives me some more time to get to a safe space or sit down.”



“I do coherent breathing for 10 minutes a day. I also use 4-7-8 breathing during the day to help balance my nervous system.”

“4 seconds inhale – 6 seconds exhale… visualizing the tension melting during exhale and physically and visually feeling my entire body melting… focusing on the cool air being inhaled and warm air being exhaled.”

ALTERNATE NOSTRIL BREATHING

Calming breathing technique where you breathe through one nostril at a time, using your fingers to gently close the other nostril.
How:
Sit comfortably and relax your shoulders
Use your right thumb to close your right nostril.
Inhale deeply through your left nostril.
Close your left nostril with your right ring finger, then exhale through your right nostril.
Inhale through your right nostril.
Close your right nostril again, then exhale through your left nostril.
Reflections:
“This helps with better sleep.”

“Helps distract from heightened anxiety and/or pain.”

BELLY BREATHING

Belly breathing, also called diaphragmatic breathing, helps you take in more oxygen and encourages the body to relax.
How:
Sit or lie down in a comfortable position.
Place one hand on your chest and the other on your abdomen.
Take a slow, deep breath in through your nose, letting the air fill your abdomen first, then your chest.
Exhale slowly through your mouth, feeling your abdomen fall.
Reflections:
“After a few minutes of diaphragmatic breathing I can feel calm and in control. Whenever I am feeling big emotions I use this type of breathing to allow myself to feel the emotion in a safe and controlled way, rather than let my emotions take over. I can let the emotion wash over me whilst breathing through it.”


HUMMING BEE BREATH 

The Humming Bee Breath uses deep breathing and a humming sound to release tension and calm the nervous system.
How:
Take a slow, deep breath in through your nose, filling your lungs completely.
Exhale with a humming sound: as you exhale, keep your mouth closed and make a humming sound, like the sound of a bee. Feel the vibration in your throat and chest.
Repeat 5+ cycles, focusing on the inhalations and the humming vibration.
Tips:
Focus on the vibration in your throat and chest
Another option is to gently cover your ears with your hands to enhance the vibration.
Reflections:
“Brings clarity when brain fog is too much.”





SOUND BREATHING
Inhale deeply and exhale with an audible sound, such as a sigh, “OM,” or other vibratory tone, to engage and calm the nervous system.
“I think OM chanting was also helpful and learning more of its benefits gave me the motivation to give that a whirl. I would take a bit more than a normal inhale and slowly exhale while saying "OM" and feeling the vibration-sensation.”
“Speech clarity: if caught just a few seconds before the start of a seizure, sound breathing can help avoid a non-epileptic seizure.”

HUMMING AND SINGING
Humming and singing use vocal vibration to soothe muscles, calm the mind, and activate the vagus nerve.


DEEP BREATHING AND EXTENDED EXHALE
Emphasizing a longer exhale than inhale to enhance the parasympathetic “rest-and-digest” response.
“Deep breath in, even longer breath out—sometimes this alone gives me enough time to reach a safe space or sit down when I feel a functional seizure coming.”

PHYSIOLOGICAL SIGH
The physiological sigh is a built-in stress-relief pattern: two quick inhales through the nose followed by a long exhale.
“Whenever I felt a quick rush of feeling overwhelmed, 2–3 physiological sighs prevented my anxiety and stress.”

VISUALIZATION MELTING BREATH
A counting-breath variation that uses imagery, visualizing tension melting away on the exhale, for deeper mind-body connection.
“I visualize my entire body melting as I exhale, focusing on cool air coming in and warm air going out, this helps me release tension without over-exerting my breath.”


SENSES

Engaging with your five senses can help stay present, improve mood, and foster a sense of calm and relaxation. This involves exteroception, which is your body's ability to sense what is happening outside of it through sight, hearing, touch, taste, and smell. It's how you perceive the world around you, like seeing a sunset, hearing music, feeling the warmth of the sun, tasting food, or smelling flowers.

“Take each day as it comes, life is a marathon not a race. Each mile will be different and that is ok. Everyone faces their marathon differently, so try not to compare your journey to that of others.”
5-4-3-2-1 GROUNDING TECHNIQUE

This technique can help you ground yourself in the present moment by guiding your focus through your senses.
How:
Look around and find:
5 things you can see
4 things you can hear
3 things you can touch
2 things you can smell
1 thing you can taste 
With each thing you encounter, gently pause and allow yourself to experience it as it is, letting a slow breath support your attention. If distracting thoughts arise, notice them, and gently bring your focus back to that sense, object, or experience.
Reflections:
“This has been really helpful when extremely stressed, anxious or feeling lost due to memory relapses.”
“Naming three things as I lie down (what I can physically see, hear and feel e.g. the bed, as I am laying down. And repeating this two more times, and then one. Then performing the same process but doing it with my eyes closed.”
NOTICE SOMETHING NEW

Looking at the familiar, or the unfamiliar, with fresh senses. This practice invites you to pause, tune into your senses, and discover what’s there.
How:
Look around your space.
Tune into your senses.
Notice if there’s anything you hadn’t noticed before (a sound, a texture, etc.).
Keep your attention on this for a few moments, notice its color, shape, texture, etc..
Describe it silently, objectively, and in a non-judgmental way to deepen your focus.
Reflections:
“I find it helpful to look around at nature and observe all the differences there are in each thing, such as each tree, each leaf, each blade of grass. No two are ever the same and by doing this it helps me to stop comparing myself to others and expecting my mind and body to do things it is not capable of just because someone else is able to.”
“Grounding or taking a slow mindful walk.”


TEXTURES TOUCH

Using tactile sensations to ground yourself by touching objects with different textures.
How:
Find a texture: Look for an object with a texture you find soothing or neutral (for example., a soft blanket, smooth stone).
Focus on touch: Spend a few moments touching the object, noticing its texture, temperature, and weight.
Describe sensations: Mentally describe the sensations you feel as you touch the object.
Tip: 
You may choose a different sense to do this exercise, such as sound, smell, etc.
Reflections:
“I use the touch sense. I carry around a token item with me, usually in my pocket, always the same item. When I am struggling due to triggers, I take the item in my hand and guide my fingers across it. Feeling every lump, bump, scratch and imperfection. Making a mental note of this, separates me from whatever is causing me to be triggered due to past trauma and brings me back to the present.”
“Touch therapy - place paralysed feet on various surfaces to stimulate feeling. Grass, carpet, tiled floor, soft towel etc. After repeated exposure I began to receive some sensory feedback and regain some sensations in my feet which had previously been paralysed for 3 years.”
“I like to tap my fingers. I use it as a distraction technique and take in how it feels if my hands/fingers feel hot, dry, cold, etc.”
“Touching moss, leaves or the water of the river.”

LISTEN TO MUSIC

Listening to music to enhance mood and relaxation.
How:
Select music that you find calming or uplifting.
Find a comfortable spot
Focus on sound
Notice details: Pay attention to different elements of the music, such as instruments, rhythm, and lyrics.
Reflections:
“Having a soothing playlist engages different senses together to create harmony and peace within.”
“Personally, what helps me the most is music. It makes me forget my symptoms at the time and focus on the music, which makes me feel very relaxed when I need calm moments.”


RAINBOW GROUNDING

A visual-mindfulness exercise that steadies attention by spotting objects in the colours of the rainbow.
How:
Wherever you are, let your gaze softly scan.
Spot objects in the colours of the rainbow: red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, and violet.
Pause with each item. Spend a few seconds noticing its shape, texture, size, or shine.
If a colour isn’t present, skip it and move on.
Reflections:
“I like to use grounding techniques such as finding things in my surroundings, for example find three objects that are red or three things that are blue in your surroundings, then keep doing that for about 5 mins. It’s quite fun but also really keeps me distracted and calm and focused.”






AROMATHERAPY
Using soothing scents to foster relaxation and grounding.
“Having something next to the bed that can help me sleep or get back from extreme nightmares/traumatic thoughts is having a soothing aromatherapy oil like lavender, a soothing textured item that reminds me of the present or a soothing lighting like a salt lamp.”
“I use aromatherapy roll-ons and Florida water to help ground me if I feel overwhelmed.”

EYES-CLOSED SIT SPOT
Closing your eyes and sitting quietly outdoors to deepen sensory awareness.
“Simply closing my eyes and sitting outside in the grass on a nice day and attempting to gain access to my senses and see what it is sensing right there and then.”
“I like to do guided meditation outside and notice the warmth of the sun on my skin, the sound and feel of the breeze, the sound of the leaves, trees and cars driving by. It brings awareness to me and my surroundings.”

HOT & COLD THERAPY
Alternating warm and cold stimuli to stimulate sensory feedback and improve circulation.
“Hot & cold therapy – I used this technique on my feet which were paralysed and had no sensation. Place feet in warm water followed by cold water. Practiced twice daily alternating for 20 minutes. After repeated exposures I began feeling sensations of heat and cold.”

SOUND THERAPY
Listening to specific sound frequencies.
“Sound therapy – I listen to brown noise at night to help promote sleep and reduce pain. I find this frequency very effective.”

SIGHT THERAPY
Performing eye movement exercises to improve visual stability and reduce dizziness.
“Sight therapy – I experience blurred vision and dizziness particularly when looking at moving objects. I practice eye movement exercises daily which has significantly improved symptoms. It mainly involves exposure to moving objects, lights, focusing on a moving target, etc.”

MINDFUL EATING
Engaging your taste sense through slow, attentive eating.
“I will often eat foods I enjoy mindfully to engage my senses. I smell the food beforehand, examine the textures, then ensure I chew completely to experience all the flavors. These small mindful activities help me stay grounded.”

FLOWER FOCUS
Using flowers to engage multiple senses—sight, smell, touch—and ground yourself.
“Flowers help me find grounding through appreciating the smell, colour, movement and shape of them. When I practice relaxed focus on flowers it resets any stress I experience.”

WALKING ON DIFFERENT TERRAINS
Stimulating sensory feedback and proprioception (the awareness of the position and movement of the body),  by walking on varied surfaces.
“One big take away for using my senses to help correct my walking. Walking on different terrain helps correct my gait, because sensing different textures under my feet refocuses my brain and distracts me from pain.”



PACING

Pacing means deliberately balancing activity with rest to conserve energy and proactively stop symptoms from flaring. By regularly pausing, noticing how your body feels, and adjusting tasks or taking breaks accordingly, you can stay within your limits and keep your body and mind steady.

A key part of effective pacing is interoception, which is your ability to sense what’s happening inside your body. This awareness helps you respond to your body's needs in real-time.


“The diagnosis of FND may seem hopeless in the moment; however, don’t lose hope. Stay consistent and take one day, sometimes one moment at a time.”


PAUSE AND CHECK-IN

Taking regular pauses to tune into your physical and emotional state.
How:
Set Reminders: Use alarms on your phone or computer as prompts to pause.
Ask Questions: Ask yourself, “How am I feeling right now?” and “What do I need?”
Observe: Notice physical sensations, emotions, or thoughts that come up.
Adjust: If you feel tension or fatigue, respond by taking a rest, sipping water, or doing a brief stretch.
Tip: 
Replace “Why am I feeling this?” with “What do I need?” / “What does my body need right now?” to remain solution-focused.
Reflections:
“I find pacing myself each day helps to ease the pain and exhaustion my body feels which leads to different symptoms to flare more. It took me a long time to realise that I cannot do everything in a day and I have to pace myself. I have found by doing this I have a lot less 'bad days' where I am unable to do anything, because I have not overdone it and pushed myself past breaking point.”
SLOW DOWN

Moving with intention and unhurried pace through each task to prevent overwhelm and maintain calm.
How:
Prioritize Tasks: Focus on one task at a time rather than juggling too many things. Consider which tasks you need to do versus those you would like to do.
Breathe Deeply: Inhale and exhale slowly as you carry out each activity.
Move Mindfully: Whether you are walking, eating, or working, consciously slow down and notice each movement.
Take Breaks: Build in small breaks throughout the day to rest and recharge. Try using one or more of the regulation strategies you find helpful during your break to proactively support your nervous system.
Reflections:
“After having a flare up and trying to walk again, I have to really pace myself, making small bits of progress which is frustrating but I have moments of feeling proud of myself.”
“Step by step.”

GUIDED RELAXATIONS

Listen to guided relaxation audios to gently relax your mind and body.
How:
Set Time: Decide how long you want your relaxation session to last.
Find Comfort: Sit or lie down in a position that feels good to you.
Choose an Audio: Pick a guided practice that meets your current needs (for example,  a Body Scan or Progressive Muscle Relaxation). You will find app suggestions for guided relaxations in the resources section.
Reflections:
“I meditate every morning which helps me with feeling calmer, more grounded and focussed on rationalising my thoughts that might be ping-ponging through my brain. It helps by self soothing limbs that might be trembling a bit. I use Insight Timer app for meditations.”

ADAPTIVE TASK PLANNING

A short, achievable to-do list each morning, or each month, can keep your days and weeks organized and prevent being overwhelmed. By focusing on what truly matters and always including at least one self-care activity, you can stay productive while honoring your limits.
How:
Morning Pause 
Before starting the day, notice how your body feels: alert, rested, tired, sore, calm, etc. and let this awareness help you match your to-do list to today’s capacity.
Draft Three Headings
Essential Tasks: essential tasks for the day.
Optional Tasks: things you will tackle only if you have extra time or energy.
Self-Care: at least one nurturing activity (for example,  bath, chat with a friend, etc.)
Limit the Load and Task Chunk
Cap “Essential-Dos” at three to five items. Break larger tasks into smaller actions to reduce feeling overwhelmed and maintain focus.
Plan Your Flow
Place focus-heavy tasks during hours you are usually more alert, energized; reserve lighter or restorative items for slower parts of the day.
Mid-Day Check & Adjust 
Glance at the list: if symptoms rise or an unexpected demand appears, reschedule lower-priority items without guilt.

Evening Review 
Tick off what’s done, note wins (especially the self-care one), and carry any unfinished essentials to tomorrow’s “Essential-Dos.”
Reflections:
“I write a realistic list of what I’d like to achieve each day starting with the important stuff but always making time to do at least one self care activity each day. This helps me to focus on what I can realistically achieve rather than become frustrated at what I can’t do which then negatively feeds my nervous system.”
“I find pacing a really important part of my weekly routine. I will often timetable in complete rest days. During these days I find it best to have as little stimulation as possible, therefore try to avoid social interaction. I enjoy exercising, but need to be wary of doing too much also. I find it’s really important to listen to my body and at certain times of the month I avoid exercise altogether. I am consistently trying to be kind, and not base my worth on how productive I have been.”
“With help from my Occupational therapist we made a list of things that I like to do but either do too much and have a boom and bust effect. Got a weekly planner, in different pens wrote what I have to do, what I'd like to do and when and how to distribute it in the week, month and 3 months, when something else came up in the day I swapped it with an item on the planner, on really symptomatic days I have list of things I can do instead, such as meditations, listen to podcast or music that is uplifting, doodle or sudoku if hands working. YouTube has many podcasts, positive affirmations, meditations and so does Spotify.”

“I find using the weekly activity schedule sheet each day helps with pacing. I write down and highlight what I’m due to do, writing down when I’ll relax, how long I’ll do each task for, and when I’ll do enjoyable tasks or when I need to change bed sheets. I also invested in a sand timer to help monitor my timing and currently use a 10 min one for each activity. Making sure to still do small tasks on bad days and relax in between.”
“I am not very good at pacing and tend to boom or bust. So I have learnt to treat myself with a reward to pace. For example, in order to stop doing too much when I feel ok, is to have a tasty snack and sit down and eat it. A bowl of cherries for example. Planning really helps too, breaking up the day with activities and rests, and being disciplined in following your plan.”

SPOON THEORY

The Spoon Theory uses the idea of “spoons” to represent energy. Each task you do, from getting dressed to cooking a meal, costs you a certain number of spoons. Once you’re out of spoons, you’ve run out of energy for the day.
How:
Count Your Spoons: Each morning, estimate how many spoons (energy units) you have for the day.
Plan Tasks: Assign a spoon cost to your daily activities based on how much energy they need.
Prioritize: Start with the most important tasks, and consider dropping or rescheduling less urgent ones if you’re running low on spoons.
Rest and Recharge: Take breaks or do gentle activities to conserve your remaining spoons or regain a little energy when possible.
Community Insights:
“Spoons. Listen to my body (& my wife). Regular naps and a good/Regular sleep routine.”
“I try to use the spoons technique where possible.”





ENERGY-TRACKING APP
Wearing a symptom-tracking / energy-monitoring app (for example,  the Visible app) to spot patterns in fatigue and identify activities that drain you.
“I wear a visible app which has helped me identify what drains me, it has really supported my pacing.”

APPOINTMENT SPACING
Ensuring appointments are not scheduled too closely to allow recovery time and prevent symptom flare-ups.
“Ensure that I do not have medical appointments too close together. I leave a three day gap for recovery if at all possible.”
“Make one appointment a day. If I do more my symptoms will flare up.”


THOUGHTS

​​Thoughts are internal mental events shaped by past experiences, present emotions, physical states, beliefs, and broader social and psychological influences.
They are not always accurate reflections of reality and do not define us, yet they can trigger emotions, influence behavior, and shape perception. 
While we cannot control when thoughts arise, we can control how to engage with them and how to respond.

”In all the confusion, overwhelm, and sense of loss, take one day at a time, one positive after another. You will rebuild your life and find ways around obstacles. Be open, curious, and brave. Your story is just starting, and amazing things lie ahead.

THOUGHT MODIFICATION AND REPLACEMENT

A technique to transform unhelpful recurring thoughts into more constructive and supportive ones.
How:
Identify a Recurrent Thought: bring to mind a thought that frequently appears and negatively impacts you.
Example: “I will always feel this way.”
Challenge the Thought 
Ask yourself:
Is this thought based on facts or assumptions? Does it help me or make me feel worse?
Realization: This thought is an assumption rooted in present discomfort rather than reality.
Modify the Thought  
Reframe it: change “I will always feel this way” to “Right now, I feel this way, but things can and do change.” 
Add a positive or neutral aspect: “I know this feeling is temporary, and I’ve gotten through it before.”
Replacement: whenever the original thought arises, replace it with the modified version.
Original: “I will always feel this way.”
Replacement: “This is temporary; I’ve seen symptoms pass before, and they will again.”



Reflections: 
“Reminding myself ‘thoughts are not my reality’ and to fixate the thought ‘whatever I am doing right now is my reality’.”

MINDFUL VISUALIZATION

A practice that blends creative imagery with mindful awareness of the spaces between thoughts, helping you transform unhelpful mental patterns into moments of calm and clarity.
How:
Settle in: find a quiet, comfortable place to sit; close your eyes and take 2–3 slow, deep breaths.
Observe your Thoughts: notice whatever thoughts arise without judging them. See them for what they are, just thoughts.
Spot the Gaps: pay attention to the brief pauses between one thought and the next; rest your awareness in those still moments, in the spaces between the thoughts.
Give Form to a Thought: choose one recurring or distressing thought and visualise it (e.g. a gray cloud).
Transform the Image: watch the image shift into something soothing (cloud breaks into sunbeams, stone blossoms into a flower).
Return to the Space: after visualising, return focus to the quiet gap; stay for a few breaths. Practise 5–10 minutes daily.
Reflections: 
“I think of my worst FND symptoms as passing clouds, they’ll dissipate.”

GRATITUDE DAILY PRACTICE

A simple exercise to cultivate positivity by reflecting on things you are grateful for.
How:
Morning Gratitude: think of three things you are grateful for in general when you wake up.
Night Gratitude: reflect on three things you are grateful for that happened during the day before going to sleep.
Visual Reminder – Choose an object in your room as a reminder. Each time you see it, let it prompt your gratitude practice
Reflections: 
“Thinking positive thoughts, practicing mindfulness, yoga, meditation and gratefulness all help to regulate my nervous system, bringing it into balance and lessen my episodes of tremors and muscle weakness.”

“The main way for me to find/reconnect with my inner peace is through gratitude”


THOUGHT DISTRACTION

A method to shift focus away from negative or distressing thoughts by engaging in pleasant activities or memories.
How:
Identify Triggers: recognise situations or thoughts that often lead to negativity.
Choose a Distraction: engage in an enjoyable activity (walking, reading, hobby, recalling a happy memory).
Immerse Yourself Fully: focus completely on the distracting activity to shift attention.
Reflections:

“Getting outside for gentle exercise is also beneficial to my mental health and acts as a great distraction.”


POSITIVE AFFIRMATIONS

A technique to reframe negative thoughts using affirmations that encourage a constructive and positive mindset.
How:
Create Affirmations: write constructive statements that counter negative thoughts, using present‑tense phrases like “I am,” “I create,” or “I move towards.”
Use Post‑Its: place chosen affirmations where you’ll see them often.
Keep an Affirmation Notebook: jot down affirmations that resonate, adding new ones every day.
Read Daily: spend a moment morning and evening reading them and visualising yourself embodying these statements.
Believe and Adjust: if an affirmation feels too “big”, tweak it (e.g. change “I am abundant” to “I am open to abundance”).
Reflections:
“I start the day with a positive affirmation. It helps set the tone for the day.”






JOURNALING AND POETRY
Writing as a way to process and reframe thoughts and emotions: spend 10–15 minutes free-writing about whatever is on your mind, or use poetry to express more complex feelings.

“Journaling has immensely helped me to keep my thoughts processed in safe way. Also having some of the resources such as challenging the negative thought patters, the wheel of emotions and worksheet printed and stuck up has helped me to keep a check on my thoughts.”

“Journaling and writing poetry helps me to be honest and acknowledge my thoughts and feelings with less judgement. It helps me to record thoughts and feelings and can make me feel better just by writing these down. I can re-read this to see how my thoughts and feelings might've changed or stayed same.”
“I journal everyday. I always notice after hand writing about difficult days or moments. I feel a sense of relief afterwards.”

THOUGHT ACCEPTANCE
Accepting thoughts without fighting them, reducing their emotional impact. Acknowledge the thought (when a negative thought arises, note it without judgment), and practice detachment (remind yourself that thoughts are not facts; they’re passing events).
“Reminding myself ‘thoughts are not my reality’ and to fixate the thought ‘whatever I am doing right now is my reality’.”

THE WORRY TREE TECHNIQUE
A structured technique to reduce overthinking and manage worries. First identify the worry and then ask yourself, “Can I do something about this?” If the answer is yes, write down the specific actions you can take; if the answer is no, practice letting it go. Once you’ve made this decision, shift your focus by doing something enjoyable or mindful to break the cycle of worry.
“I like to journal my thoughts and write down in a diary my thoughts each day… If you can’t do anything about the worry then you have to let the worry go. Then distract yourself and do something enjoyable.”

TRANSACTIONAL ANALYSIS (TA)
A psychological approach that can help you recognize the three ego states—Parent, Adult, and Child—that can shape your thoughts and behavior. Throughout the day, check in with yourself to see which state you’re in. If you notice feeling distressed or reactive, gently shift into the Adult state by grounding yourself in the present and focusing on calm, rational thinking.
“I have never had an FND episode when I am in “adult”, therefore I will aim to get back into adult life if I do feel myself slipping into a distressed or agitated state.”

ACCEPTANCE & COMMITMENT THERAPY (ACT)
This approach can help you accept your thoughts and feelings instead of fighting them, while choosing actions that match what matters most to you. The practice involves noticing thoughts as just thoughts, staying present in the moment, and taking small, purposeful steps guided by your values.
“I did incorporate ACT (acceptance commitment therapy)… I attempted to adapt to self‑love and self‑compassion.”

LETTER‑WRITING TO THOUGHTS 
This technique can help lessen the power of worrying or unhelpful thoughts by writing them a letter. Start by addressing the thought directly, like “Dear worry…,” then describe how it affects you. Next, set boundaries by stating what you will and won’t allow. Finally, either keep the letter in a safe place or discard it to let it go.


“I wrote a letter regarding them and how I feel about them. For example, I'd write down ‘can you just go in the other room or go out somewhere? If you think you are helping, you really aren't helping me at all. Let me and my present handle the big stuff.’ Making it seem that it is not in charge or has high authority to make calls.”


MOVEMENT

Movement can be a powerful way to enhance both mental and physical well-being. By actively engaging in physical activities, whether gentle or more vigorous, we can release tension, improve mood, increase energy levels, and promote overall health.



“Don’t focus on what’s gone; focus on what can be introduced, what can be added and what can be learnt. Change is good!”

(Note: Please listen to your body and do only what feels comfortable and safe for you. Physical activity looks different for everyone, and even gentle or modified activities still count as movement and exercise.)
SELF-SOOTHING TOUCH AND MOVEMENT

Using gentle touches, strokes, or slight movements to calm the body and mind.
How:
Choose a Comfortable Position: sit or lie down.
Begin with Light Strokes: gently stroke arms, legs, face,  or any other area.
Combine With Gentle Movement: if comfortable, move or sway the body part you’re touching.
Breathe Deeply: inhale and exhale slowly while stroking.
Reflections: 
“This is a wonderful practice for regulating the nervous system and allowing our bodies to come into a calmer state. I use it often, even when not distressed, to maintain and regulate.”
“Self soothing – stroking arms and legs to reduce trembling and ease nerves and muscles.”
“This is a very calming technique that is extremely self-soothing and comforting. These movements of both my body and breathing, bring my mind to really slow down too.”
SHAKE-AND-TAP RELEASE

A technique combining gentle rhythmic shaking with light tapping to wake up the body, boost circulation, release tension, and bring you into the present moment.
How:
Feet Grounded (optional): stand or sit with feet hip-width apart, firmly planted.
Hands & Arms – Shake: shake your hands vigorously for 15–30 seconds, then your forearms and upper arms together, letting any tension “jiggle” out.
Hands & Arms – Tap: switch to tapping your chest and then tap along your arms from shoulders to wrists for 15–30 seconds.
Legs – Shake: shake one leg at a time (15–30 seconds each), then both together if able, letting the energy flow through your hips and thighs.
Legs – Tap: follow with tapping your thighs and calves for 15–30 seconds.
Full Body – Shake: gently shake your whole body for 20–40 seconds, softening your knees and allowing your spine, torso, and head to move freely.
Full Body – Tap: conclude by light, whole-body tapping, running your hands over your shoulders, torso, legs, and arms as if brushing away tension.
Tip:
If you prefer, you can do all the shaking first and then follow with tapping (or vice versa) to suit your comfort and rhythm.





Reflections:
“I started to use the tapping technique after attending the mindfulness course with Irene through FND hope. I was initially very skeptical. However I was intrigued also and so started to practice it. I now use it when struggling with pain, it helps me to focus on the tapping instead of the pain which in turn helps me relax and become less tense.”
“A very activating practice. Great for bringing you back into your body and into the present moment.”


DANCING

Moving freely to music for fun, expression, and releasing energy.
How:
Choose Music: select songs that make you want to move.
Create Space: find a safe, open area for dancing.
Move Freely: dance in whatever way feels good to you, without worrying about technique. Let your body take the lead and move naturally to the rhythm of the music. 
Enjoy: focus on the freedom of movement.
Reminder: Dancing can happen while sitting down too.
Reflections: 
“Chakra dancing.”
“If I have enough balance, I try dancing or, if seated, I move my whole body without worrying about steps and without looking in the mirror—actually, it’s often better if I can do it with my eyes closed.”
“I paint, draw, dance and sing as a form of self care.”
“Dancing makes me focus on the music and the steps, which improves my symptoms.” 


BRUSH TECHNIQUE

Sweeping your hand along a body part, as if brushing away dust or excess energy.
How:
Find a comfortable position (sitting or standing).
Place one hand on your shoulder or thigh.
Slowly sweep your hand downward, toward fingertips or the end of the body part.
Visualize tension being brushed away with each stroke.
Repeat several times on each side.
Reflections:

“After this practice I feel soothed, relaxed and calmer. I will often sigh naturally because it is so soothing.”
“This is a technique that I do often and love. I can feel the release of what is being held in my energy field with each brush.”
“Similar to the Tai Chi I was introduced to whilst on FMD rehabilitation programme.”


STRETCHING

Extending and flexing muscles to maintain or improve flexibility.
How:
Warm Up: do a brief warm-up first (for example,  gentle marching in place or swinging your arms).
Target Areas: focus on major muscle groups like legs, back, and shoulders.
Hold Stretches: hold each stretch for 15–30 seconds.
Breathe: inhale to lengthen the stretch, exhale to relax more deeply into it.
Regular Practice: aim for daily or frequent stretching.
Reflections:
“I try to do some simple stretches as I wake up and before bed. I definitely feel they help and have reduced the frequency of my severe pain.”
“I feel more energized and stronger within my body after doing this practice.”
“As long as I move incredibly slowly and with great intention I can accomplish stretching without tremors or body jerking.”
“I find stretching helpful to soothe me, release tension and it also helps keep my body in condition so it's better able to support itself. Depending on my symptoms I might not be able to do it everyday, but I've found that anything helps and adds up.”






SIMPLE TECHNIQUE 
The Simple Technique (also known as the Basic Exercise) is a gentle way to calm your nervous system by stimulating the vagus nerve. To practice it, lie down or sit comfortably and place your hands behind your head, letting your elbows relax outward. Without moving your head, slowly shift your eyes to one side and hold your gaze there until you naturally sigh, yawn, or feel a release of tension. Then bring your eyes back to the center and repeat on the other side. This exercise can help the body move out of stress and into a more relaxed, balanced state.
“This helps activate the parasympathetic nervous system, brings calm to the nervous system, and helps with anxiety.”

OTHER REFLECTIONS ABOUT MOVEMENT PRACTICES: 
“I am a wheelchair user but I find seated Pilates incredibly fulfilling. I also do seated strength and cardio training – lots of videos on YouTube. Exercise helps me to feel more positive mentally. I do have to be careful to pace my activity. Getting outside for gentle exercise is also beneficial to my mental health and acts as a great distraction.”
“Keeping my body active through exercise, walking, running, lifting weights, and Yoga are helpful for my mind and body. Getting out of my head and into my body helps me relieve stress and helps my body release endorphins, serotonin and dopamine.”
“Moving around while hugging a Pilates ball helps me.”
“Chair and bed Yoga has helped with my movement.”
“Slow movements such as tai chi helped in the past as I closed my eyes. I was able to feel my arms gliding as they were extended fully, the bending of my knees, and trunk of my body. I tried to visualize as I had my eyes closed, something that resembles ‘smoothness’ without any ‘rigids’ from occurring. Sort of like smooth water waves.”
“Somatic yoga, yin yoga, kundalini yoga, swimming and walking if able.”
“Seated yoga. Walking – gentle non weight bearing exercise.”
“Rock climbing has always been a type of physiotherapy that has assisted me with FND symptoms. When I am climbing my mind and body are connected as one. Every movement I make is considered and each limb is placed exactly right. I have to be hyper focused on what movement I will do next to ensure I get to the top of a rock climb. There is no room for error and it demands a high level of concentration and mental strength. During an FND episode I can feel completely disconnected from my body and out of control. Therefore when I am climbing I am reminding my body of how to be connected and in control. I find it very empowering and effective in keeping FND symptoms at bay. It also gives me immense confidence mentally and physically that my body is capable of amazing things.”
“Yoga, dance therapy, and walking in nature help me release emotions and improve my balance.” 



ARTS

Engaging in arts can be a powerful way to express emotions, reduce stress, and enhance overall well-being. Creative practices can invite you into the present moment, grounding your awareness in colour, shape, texture, or words as they unfold. They can give shape to feelings that are hard to name and leave a tangible reminder of your resourcefulness. 



“Write a list of things that you enjoy doing. Choose one and do it today!"



ART JOURNALING

Combining words, sketches, colours, and images in a journal creates a space for expression, reflection, and play. Art journaling can help organise feelings, track progress, and provide a safe outlet for creativity without pressure.
How:
Choose a Notebook/Sketchbook.
Use Mix of Styles: writing, doodling, painting, or collage on each page.
Let Go of Rules: pages can be abstract, messy, or colourful.
Add Text: affirmations, quotes, or daily reflections.
Revisit Past Entries: see how your art journal changes over time.
Reflections:
“Art Journal, watercolor painting, doodling, gratitude journal, neurographic art therapy, knitting, colouring and mandala art. All forms of art are helpful as it helps connect more than 2 senses and create new neural pathways.”

COLLAGE MAKING

Assemble images, colours and words into a single picture that captures your mood, a memory or a dream.
How:
Gather Materials: magazines, newspapers, coloured paper, fabric scraps, photos, glue, scissors, a sheet of card, etc.
Choose a Theme: e.g. “strength”, “calm”, “future goals”, or simply follow whatever catches your eye.
Cut and Arrange: trim or tear elements and play with placement until the story on the page feels right.
Glue and Layer: secure the pieces, adding paint, pens or stitching if you wish.
Reflect: notice any emotions, memories or insights the finished collage evokes.
Reflections: 
“The act of choosing a theme, selecting pictures or items that represent that theme to you - can be a big help in a few different ways for me. To slow my thoughts down as I am selecting the materials, making me think about what theme I am doing the artwork towards, the process of playing around with the items for the collage, and putting them into sequence. Overall this aid can cover so many different processes and help me feel calmer and more motivated.”
“I use creativity in many ways to support my healing. I have found that this is the number one way to bring light into this journey.”  
COLOURING

Engaging in colouring can channel attention into a simple, creative task, helping to quiet the mind, release tension, and improve fine motor skills.
How:
Choose Your Materials: select a colouring book or printable designs and gather coloured pencils, markers, or crayons.
Create A Calm Space: find a quiet spot free of distractions and set aside some time.
Colour Mindfully: focus on each stroke, notice the pressure, the movement, and the emerging hues.
Let Go Of Perfection: remind yourself that colouring “outside the lines” is fine; the goal is relaxation, not a perfect picture.
Reflect: when you finish, take a moment to observe how your mood or tension levels have shifted.
Reflections: 
“I bought a random adult coloring book and bought a set of markers and colored pencils...I tried to remind myself as I was coloring that "it does not have to be perfect. This is a time for you to simply release tension or steam". I would doodle and not think... Just to act and not think. Helped with the overthinking and the perfectionism to a grade”
“Colouring or paper mache, even though they can be tricky during a flare up. They are mindful and help me feel productive.”

“I love colouring books for adults. I’ve purchased two and have pencils. It keeps me calm and relaxed.”


CRAFTING WITH NATURAL MATERIALS

Bring nature indoors and let them guide your creativity.
How:
Forage Mindfully: leaves, twigs, shells, stones, seed-pods (avoid protected plants).
Pick a Project: a nature collage, drift-wood mobile, painted pebble, etc.
Arrange and Secure: use biodegradable glue, string or wire.
Reflect: notice any sense of connection or grounding the materials evoke.
Reflections: 
“This practice helps to bring me back into my body and ground me in the present moment. I have to focus on what I'm doing, as well as the textures. This allows me to connect with my body, as well as being fully present in what I'm doing.”
“Working with wood relaxes me a lot (restoring doors, making furniture), sculpture or writing (I express all my feelings in it). I create sculptures based on how I feel or if I need to heal a trauma, I capture it in the sculpture.”

DOODLING FOR RELAXATION

Aimless marks that free the hand and let thoughts drift by without judgment.
How:
Settle Somewhere Quiet, with pen and paper.
Let the Pen Wander: loops, spirals, zig-zags, cartoon shapes, etc.
Stay Present and Curious: if the mind starts to criticise, return attention to the moving line.
Optional Colour-wash: add highlighters or water-colours over the top.
Pause and Observe: How do you feel now? What did you notice about your thoughts as you doodled? etc.
Reflections: 
“I would doodle and not think... Just to act and not think. Helped with overthinking and perfectionism to a grade. Both were helpful with my symptoms to a certain extent.”

“Being creative takes my mind away from anything that is happening in the everyday that I am finding overwhelming. It helps me to step away from whatever is going on and to focus on something different. When I am doing something creative, whether it is drawing, painting, card-making ect, I am able to push everything else out of my head and focus on that one task, it stops me from spending hours overthinking.”






PAINTING & DRAWING
Using brushes, pencils or pens to translate emotion onto paper or canvas.
“I paint, draw, dance and sing as a form of self care. Doing something creative daily helps my motor skills and promotes mental wellbeing.”
“Writing, painting, or even reading helps a lot with relaxation and anxiety symptoms.”

NEURO GRAPHIC ART
Drawing free-flowing lines and rounding intersections to create organic, web-like images that soothe the mind.
“I have started sharing neurographic art with my friends and even they find that it helps calming, relaxing and thinking clearly. Helpful for pain relief and brain fog.”

DIAMOND ART / STICKER PUZZLES
Placing tiny resin “gems” or stickers onto a coded canvas to build a sparkling mosaic/image  that rewards patience and precision.

PERFORMANCE & DANCE ARTS
Expressive art through movement or music.
“Staying creative with a chronic illness can be challenging but also vital for keeping a good mental wellbeing. I do this by creating dance routines; using movements I know my own body can handle.”


SOCIAL

Meaningful social connections can play a vital role in our overall well-being. Building and maintaining strong relationships with family, friends, and community can provide emotional support, reduce stress, improve mental health and support nervous system regulation. Engaging in social activities helps create a sense of belonging and can positively impact FND.

“You are not alone! FND can feel very overwhelming, sometimes it feels like no one really understands you. But you are not alone. Joining a peer support group can help you talk about struggles and find new information about living with FND. The care for patients with FND is not up to standard but more and more caregivers are learning about FND and more research is getting done. There is hope! We are going in the right direction.”

TIME WITH A FRIEND

A brief, regular catch-up with someone who makes you feel at ease.
How:
Choose a Friend: someone who leaves you feeling supported or uplifted.
Pick a Time: choose a slot in your diary when you can give full attention.
Reach Out
Enjoy the Company: chat, laugh, vent, listen. Stay present.
Reflections: 
“Socializing with friends, talking, eating together, going for a walk, run, or cup of coffee helps me to feel happy. Being with people is important to our overall health.”
“Walking with friends/family and being in nature makes me feel better. Seeing friends/phone befriending takes my mind off any symptoms if having a flare up.”

CREATING A SUPPORT MAP

A support map makes it easier to see who you can turn to for different kinds of help.
How:
Put your name in the centre of a page.
Add the names of family, friends, professionals, or online groups around it.
Note the type of support each gives (listening, practical help, medical advice).
Use colours or circles to group people.
Update the map as things change.
Reflections: 
“It's incredibly helpful to visualize or map out your support network. In times of distress you can easily see or visualize who might be most helpful to reach out to.”
“My map was very limited at the beginning of my journey and is filling in little by little as I go forward. I've met some incredible people that I would otherwise never have known.”
“This is a really unique aid for my mind - especially during times when my brain is feeling foggy and I can't think straight. To have this visual representation of my supporters at hand is an extremely valuable help.”
JOINING COMMUNITY AND SUPPORT GROUPS
Linking with people who share your interests and/or diagnosis can help you feel understood and supported. It can create a sense of belonging and provide a safe space to exchange experiences, coping strategies, and encouragement.
How:
Identify Interests: hobbies, faith, condition-specific groups.
Search Options: via community centres, social media, FND charities, etc.
Attend a Meeting: online or in person.
Participate Actively: ask questions, offer skills, volunteer for small roles.
Nurture Friendships beyond formal sessions.
Reflections: 
“Having seizures or tremors can be very isolating. Talking to people going through similar things can really help with coping. “ 
“I find FND Facebook groups a good way of connecting with others. I have also participated in webinars with other people with FND.”

“Peer support groups have really been helpful, not feeling that I'm alone in this, exchange help and be able to share our stories and hear others in same boat.”
“I have built up a small community online with other people who also experience FND symptoms… Talking to others I have realised that it’s not me that should be ashamed.”
ENGAGING IN ACTS OF KINDNESS

Small, spontaneous gestures that lift both giver and receiver.
How:
Spot Opportunities: hold a door, offer a genuine compliment, send a supportive text.
Act Without Expectation of return thanks or favour.
Pause to Notice the warm after-glow in your body.
Encourage a Ripple: share the idea with friends or family.
Weave Kindness in daily life to keep social bonds vibrant.
Reflections: 
“Helping others within my capabilities also really helps me feel better about myself.”
“I've always found this practice very helpful. It shifts my focus to other people and sharing acts of kindness allows me to feel gratitude as well as a sense of belonging with others.”

VOLUNTEER

Offering time or skills to a cause that resonates with you.
How:
Choose a Cause: find an issue or community that matters to you.
Offer Your Skills: identify what you can contribute: time, talent, resources, etc..
Make a Plan: set realistic goals and commit time regularly.
Reflect and Connect: notice the impact, meet people, and enjoy giving back.
Reflections: 
“I find volunteering helps me to feel a sense of accomplishment and giving back to the community. As well as being able to connect with the community more while doing so and deepening those relationships as I go.”








OPEN AND HONEST COMMUNICATION
Being open and honest about what you need and how others can help, as well as honest with yourself about your current limitations and capacity.
“I find it best to be open and honest with friends and family – ask for support if you are struggling to access social opportunities.”
“Tell friends what they could do to help you if you have a seizure, ensure they know your triggers and how to support you.”

SMALL POSITIVE GROUP CHAT
Joining or forming a private online chat with peers to share encouragement, humour, and daily support.
“We have a small group of people, all with similar interests and warm personalities on a private group chat. We focus on sharing positive thoughts and experiences and encouraging one another… Having a small positive group really helps have a place where people understand and are really cheering for you.”

LANGUAGE LEARNING WITH OTHERS
Practicing or learning a foreign language in a group to reduce isolation and build skills together.
“Speaking a language that is not your own, or learning it with others, has helped me improve symptoms of depression and anxiety.”

CALM LISTENING
Taking the time to be present and patient with others, especially during moments of stress.
“Taking time to listen and keep calm and patience.”


NUTRITION

Consistent, nutrient-rich eating and proper hydration can steady energy, improve cognitive function, lift mood, and support nervous-system regulation.

“Be compassionate towards yourself, rest more, do activities which increase happy hormones like DOSE (Dopamine, Oxytocin, Serotonin, Endorphin), drink plenty of water, walk in nature and pace your activities. You are not alone. Ask for help.”


(Note: The ideas below offer general guidance, not personal medical advice. Consult your GP or dietitian before changing your diet or nutrition plan.)
BALANCED MEAL PLANNING

Organising each meal so it contains a healthy mix of proteins, complex carbohydrates, beneficial fats, vitamins and minerals.
How:
Get Familiarised with the Food Groups: protein, complex carbs, healthy fats, fruit & veg, dairy/alternatives.
Plan a Week of Meals: write a simple menu or batch-cook staples so balanced options are always ready.
Mind Portions: use smaller plates or measuring cups if helpful.
Keep it Colourful: different colours usually mean different micronutrients.
Reflections
“Healthy balanced diet. High protein, high fibre. Lots of nutrients from fruits and vegetables.”
“By having a healthy and balanced diet I find that my body gets less fatigued than when I was eating a lot more processed and junk food.”
“I believe the body can be healed by good food and it can be a huge determinant of health.”
“While I was still working I had some warnings that led to hypertension and I decided I had to organise my diet in quantity, variety and timing. With my nutritionist we developed a plan of three meals a day and what works best for me is a portion of protein, a portion of vegetables and a portion of fruit for breakfast, lunch and dinner… I think it has prevented worse problems.”
“Eating more healthily—without gluten, almost no sugar, no cow’s milk, with lots of fruit, vegetables, ginger, turmeric… And respecting 5 meals a day to keep fairly stable schedules.”

MINDFUL EATING

Bringing full, non-judgemental attention to the sights, smells, textures, and flavours of food can support digestion, enhance enjoyment, and help you feel more present and regulated.
How:
Eat Slowly: chew thoroughly and pause between bites.
Remove Distractions: no phone, TV or computer.
Notice the Senses: colour, aroma, temperature, texture, flavour.
Check in: stop when you feel comfortably satisfied.
Reflections: 
“I will often eat foods I enjoy mindfully to engage my senses. I will smell the food beforehand, examine the different textures, then ensure I chew the food completely allowing me to experience all the flavours. These small mindful activities during the day allow me to stay grounded - which is really important to ward of FND symptoms.”



HYDRATION ROUTINE

Keeping hydrated supports overall physical and emotional well-being.
How:
Begin the morning with a full glass of water.
Carry a refillable bottle everywhere.
Set reminders to drink water
Flavour water with lemon, mint, cucumber or berries if that encourages you to drink.
Reflections: 
“I have an app that  helps me monitor my water intake”
“Drinking tea can feel like 'me time' and is calming.”
“Drinking enough fluid - water in particular, is an important part of my day. On days when I don't get enough to drink, I can start to feel agitated and ill.”


SMART BLOOD-SUGAR BALANCING

Reducing added sugars and choosing foods that release glucose steadily can help minimise crashes, fatigue, brain-fog and symptom flare-ups.
How:
Read Labels: spot hidden sugars in sauces, dressings and packaged snacks.
Whole-foods First: fruit, vegetables, legumes, minimally processed grains.
Pair Carbs with Protein or Healthy Fat: apple + almond butter, oats + Greek yogurt.
Favour Low-GI Carbs: sweet potato, quinoa, brown rice, whole fruit.
Add Fibre: chia seeds, beans or extra veg at each meal.
Swap Wisely: for example, berries instead of sugar for sweetness or sparkling water instead of soda or juice.
Taper Gradually: let taste buds adjust week by week.
Track Reactions: note any link between high-sugar foods and symptom flare-ups.
Reflections: 
“Eating more protein and cutting out sugar and wheat from my diet has helped decrease my tremors significantly.”

“I find that when I omit processed sugar, gluten, cow’s milk, alcohol and caffeine I always feel better, I have more energy and my moods are easier to regulate.”

“A low-carbohydrate diet.”

GUT-FRIENDLY FOCUS 

Feeding your gut in ways that also support your brain, mood, immunity, and overall resilience.
How:
Include fermented food in your diet (live yogurt, kefir, kimchi, sauerkraut, miso).
Feed beneficial bacteria with prebiotic fibres like onions, garlic, leeks, bananas, oats, etc.
Rotate choices for a broader range of microbes.
Drink plenty of water to help fibre do its job.
Reflections: 
“Following the Mediterranean diet as fully as possible helps with my gut, stomach and overall well-being.”

MAGNESIUM & B-VITAMIN BOOST

Prioritising nutrients that ease muscle tension and support healthy nerve signalling.
How:
Eat Magnesium-rich Foods: dark leafy greens, pumpkin seeds, almonds, black beans, dark chocolate (70 %+), etc.
Add B-vitamin Sources: whole grains, eggs, legumes, nutritional yeast, leafy greens, etc.
Pair with vitamin C foods (citrus, peppers) to aid certain B-vitamin absorptions.
Reflections: 
“I am severely allergic to many foods so this is difficult but I worked with a dietician to understand nutrients that are important for brain function and nervous system function and ensure that my diet contains plenty of B vitamins, vitamin D etc and if this is not possible I take supplements.”





CAFFEINE & ALCOHOL MODERATION
Limiting stimulants and depressants that can disrupt sleep and exacerbate symptoms.
“No Caffeine after 12pm & limited alcohol. Lots of fruit & fibre. I struggle to balance my diet with needs of comorbid conditions. The latest challenge is to integrate pre-diabetes with the other things that are going on.”

VEGAN NUTRITION
Adopting a plant-based diet to improve energy, mood and pain levels.
“Having become vegan has helped me, especially feeling more energetic and managing my anger. Dairy seemed to make my symptoms worse… since becoming vegan in the last 4 years I have seen improvement in my energy levels, mood swings, and less pain.”
STRUCTURED EATING ROUTINE
Maintaining regular eating times and steady meal rhythms to stabilise energy and mood.
“With my nutritionist we developed a plan of three meals a day… decaf coffee or tea, one apple a day, herbal teas, and the more natural the food the better.”

FOOD & MOOD AWARENESS
Noticing and tracking how different foods affect energy, motivation, and symptoms.
“I did notice if I ate fast food, for example, I did feel lethargic and not as motivated to do anything which increased my depressive symptoms to a higher percent.”


NATURE

Nature-based practices can be a practical ally. Even a few minutes of fresh air, feeling grass under bare feet or watching clouds drift past, can calm the nervous system, brighten mood, and restore a sense of spaciousness. The techniques that follow show how to weave outdoor moments into your daily routine and turn them into steady sources of regulation and relief.


“Life isn’t over, it’s just different. And in this new space you will find all sorts of wonderful and amazing things that wouldn’t have come into your life without FND. It’s not all bad; finding strategies, friends and new ways of thinking will add to your life.”

NATURE OBSERVATION

Quietly attend to the living landscape around you to deepen mindfulness and ease tension.
How:
Find a Spot: sit or stand somewhere safe and comfortable (park bench, garden chair, forest log).
Sense Quietly: let the eyes wander; note colours, shapes, movements. Tune in to scent, touch, sound.
Take Notes or Sketch: optional, but recording details can sharpen attention.
Reflect and Ask: What did I notice? Was there anything that surprised me? Was there anything I learned from it?
Reflections: 
“Walking in the parks and woods is helpful in calming and relaxing the mind, fresh air helps better breathing and feeling grounded.”
“I find it helpful to look around at nature and observe all the differences there are in each thing, such as each tree, each leaf, each blade of grass. No two are ever the same and by doing this it helps me to stop comparing myself to others and expecting my mind and body to do things it is not capable of just because someone else is able to. Specifically someone who also has FND or something similar.”

GARDENING

Hands-on care of plants can offer rhythmic movement, purposeful focus and a tangible sense of growth.
How:
Choose Plants: pick species you love and that thrive in your climate.
Prepare Soil and Plant: work the earth, sow or pot seedlings.
Regular Care: water, weed, prune and harvest mindfully.
Enjoy the Process: notice scent of soil, texture of leaves, colours unfolding.
Reflections: 
“Gardening allows me to feel productive, engages my senses and refocuses my brain.”
“Walking, gardening or sitting in the garden.”

NATURE KEEPSAKE

Selecting a small natural object, stone, feather, shell, pinecone to carry as a tactile “anchor.” You keep it until it feels like its lesson or comfort is complete, then return it to the earth with gratitude.
How:
Mindful Gathering: during a walk, let your attention settle on an item that feels inviting. Pick it up if it’s abundant and you’re allowed to remove it.
Set an Intention: hold the keepsake in both hands. Silently name what support you’d like it to offer (for example,  calm, courage, grounding).
Daily Touch-In: carry the object in a pocket or bag. Whenever symptoms rise, roll it between fingers, tracing every contour while taking three slow breaths.
Reflect on Its Teaching: at day’s end, or weekly, journal how the object’s texture, weight, or symbolism helped you navigate moments.
Release Ritual: when you sense the keepsake has “done its job,” return it to a natural setting or place it on a home altar with thanks, making space for a new lesson when needed.
Reflections: 
“During this practice I feel connected with the earth, which is grounding. The smoothness of the stone I chose reminds me to be gentle with myself and slow down so I'm able to release tension and regulate my nervous system.”


“I often choose something with a smooth surface and that helps to calm my nervous system while holding/exploring it. This practice has helped to ground me or soothe me while going through something intense.”

GROUNDING WALK 

Barefoot contact with grass, sand, or soil can promote a sense of calm and provide novel sensory input, which may be helpful for grounding and supporting the nervous system’s ability to become more regulated and adaptable.
How:
Choose a Safe Surface: grass, sandy beach, quiet woodland clearing.
Remove Footwear and Stand: notice temperature and texture underfoot.
Walk Slowly: shift weight heel-to-toe; keep knees soft.
Breathe and Sense: with each step mentally note a sensation (cool, soft, grainy).
Close Gently: after 5–10 minutes, pause, thank the Earth, clean your feet.
Variation: if standing or walking is not possible today, rest/sit outdoors (or by an open window) and place your bare feet or hands on soil, grass, or a potted plant, noticing the sensations for the same 5–10 minutes.
Reflections: 
“Sensory feedback from nature - walking on grass, touching bark, waking on sand etc has helped me regain feeling in my limbs. I find being out in nature calming in general. I go for mindfulness walks outside to support my mental health and lower my stress levels.”
“I feel very calm when I do this, I especially love burying my feet and hands in sand (when I'm able to). I do notice a physical difference during and after.”
BLUE-SPACE PAUSE

Resting beside water (lake, river, fountain, sea) invites a “blue-mind” state of gentle focus and lowered heart-rate.
How:
Locate Water: any safe, accessible body of water.
Settle in: sit or stand where sight and sound of water are clear.
Soft Gaze: watch ripples or reflections without fixing on one point.
Match the Rhythm: breathe in as water rises or flows toward you; breathe out as it recedes.
Lengthen Presence: stay 5–15 minutes; leave slowly, carrying the calm.
Reflections: 
“Being outside, especially next to the water or ocean is my happy space. My body feels at peace listening to the waves crashing against the shore.”
“I find forests, woods, waterfalls, the sea, lakes any nature grounding and increases my wellbeing.”
“Being immersed in nature is vital to my well-being and for keeping FND symptoms at bay. I will often travel to the beach, forest / woods, up onto the hill to just breathe. I find greenery or the blues of the sea so calming for my nervous system. I also enjoy immersing myself in cold water, which I find gives me a boost and ignites my day.”
“Go to the beach or see the sea and hear the waves.”
“Refreshing my legs or swimming has a total therapeutic effect”
“Sitting in the ocean (or any water, including shower/bath or even just rinsing your hands) and allowing/intending/visualizing the water to "wash away" my pain or surrender emotional pain and allow it to be taken away by the water (even if just for a few seconds-minutes). This can be done visually, or by intention because I know not everyone is able to visualize or even fully imagine something.”





FREE NATURE WANDERING
Allowing your body to guide you on an unstructured walk, no destination, no pace goal, just curiosity and presence.
“Walking outside simply anywhere...wherever my body would lead me to (me not holding any restrictions, giving it freedom and trying not to have a thought alter my direction).”
“Walking in the forest preferably alone.”
“Just finding a place to sit still in nature and observe really helps ground myself. I believe fresh air is so important for the nervous system and being in a large outdoor scene really helps put life into perspective.”
“Walking and walking through the forest or near the sea or in the mountains, breathing that pure air… has a total therapeutic effect.”
“Walking in the countryside for at least an hour… It gives me joy and a desire to live, and if it’s in the countryside with only the birds, it helps with my tinnitus symptoms.”



COMPASSION

Compassion means treating both yourself and others with warmth, patience, and understanding, especially in the face of challenging situations. Research shows that self-compassion lowers stress hormones, calms the nervous system, and supports emotional recovery.



“Be kind to yourself. Be compassionate to yourself. Be patient with yourself. Give yourself time to understand the condition. FND doesn’t define you.”

STRENGTHS & ACHIEVEMENTS MAP

This practice invites you to look back at positive experiences, no matter how small, and notice the personal strengths that helped you through. 
How:
Think of a recent achievement or moment you managed well. Write down what happened.
Next, note the personal strength you used (e.g. patience, perseverance, creativity).
Add a sentence about how that strength showed itself in practice.
Finally, pause and notice what emotions arise as you remember this experience.
Repeat this with a few more examples, then look back: do some strengths appear regularly? 
Reflections: 
“I would hand write (no typing) encouraging words to myself (a letter in the third person)… pointing out all of the things that I had accomplished and completed to feel a sense of pride and to decrease the numb feeling.”

LOVING-KINDNESS MEDITATION

A brief, phrase-based meditation that starts with goodwill toward yourself and gradually radiates it to others, strengthening empathy circuits and easing reactivity.
How:
Sit comfortably, eyes closed.
Take three slow breaths; bring attention to your heart.
Silently repeat for 2–3 min:
“May I be safe.”
“May I be peaceful.”
“May I be healthy.”
“May I live with ease.”
Picture a loved one; repeat the phrases for them, then for a neutral person, a difficult person, and finally “all beings.”
Rest for a few breaths and notice any change in mood or body tension.
Practice 5 min daily, increasing time as comfortable.
Reflections: 
“​​I enjoy meditation a lot and this type helps keep me calm and is a reminder to show myself kindness and to others always.”
“I start the day with a positive affirmation. It helps set the tone for the day. I also practice self-compassion techniques and have found this particularly helpful on the days where my body shuts down or isn’t functioning well.”

COMPASSIONATE BODY SCAN

A gentle head-to-toe practice that combines mindful awareness with kind, supportive language, helping you notice sensations and areas of tension with curiosity and without judgment.
How:
Lie down or sit with back support: close your eyes.
Start at the crown: “Hello, head. Thank you for what you do,” then soften the area.
Move downward (forehead, eyes, jaw…) offering phrases like “May you feel ease.”
If you notice discomfort, rest a hand there and sigh out an “ahhh.”
Finish at the feet: “Thank you, body, for carrying me today.”
A 10-min timer or soft music can keep the pace.

Reflections
“This practice has been incredibly helpful over the years to be able to connect with and check in with pain areas of my body and be able to focus positively towards my body for what it can do. This can allow me to shift how I'm processing the world and my pain.”
”I’ve been doing body scans for a while, they are very helpful as it’s a way to connect with my body and notice how it feels even if you don’t feel good acknowledging and having a non judgmental approach. Adding verbal kindness is really good, especially on my bad days. It’s good to always notice the good in life even on hard days.”
THE “COMPASSION PAUSE” CARD

A pocket card (or phone screenshot) with three self-questions that interrupt harsh self-talk in real time.
How:
Write on a small card:
What am I feeling right now?
What do I need?
What is the kindest next step?
Keep it in your wallet, desk, or phone.
When stress spikes, place a hand on your chest, read the questions, answer honestly, and act on question 3 (ex: stretch, sip water, text a friend, rest, etc).
Notice any shift in tension or mood.
Reflections: 
“I think it’s important to remember, anything that’s not done in compassion when you are struggling, isn’t helping. Sometimes being disciplined can be a form of compassion too, as long as you remember it’s for your good and isn’t a punishment. I think compassion is often asking yourself what you need, rather than criticism which asks if you’re good enough.”
“I've done this practice for years and find it incredibly helpful to check in with myself when stressful events happen, or just throughout the day. It helps me connect with myself and become more grounded in my body, rather than feeling scattered all over the place.”


SELF-COMPASSION LETTER

A private letter that speaks to your own needs with the kindness you would offer someone you love.
How:
Pen and paper.
Hand on Heart: take a nice slow breath and ask yourself “What do I need right now?” and write down whatever comes to your mind (with  no filter).
Pause. 
Hand on your Heart Again: ask “What would I like to hear?” and let supportive phrases flow. Write them all down (no filter/editing).
Read the letter back slowly, welcoming each word. You deserve them all. 
Note: You deserve every word of kindness you just wrote. If this feels awkward at first, that’s ok. Self-compassion can take practice.
Reflections: 
“I am learning to love myself and speak to myself as I do to people I love.”





POSITIVE AFFIRMATIONS & SELF-TALK
Repeating kind statements throughout the day (or writing them on post-its or in a notebook and reading them often) can help to strengthen self-esteem and bring a sense of calm.
“Mindfulness practice and Self talk is very important to me. Saying nice things to myself when I’ve completed a task or did something even if I was having a bad day. I also listen to positive affirmations and recite them which can build self-confidence and self-esteem.”

ANGER-SOOTHING COMPASSION
Deliberately shifting from anger to a compassionate mindset can prevent symptom flare-ups triggered by stress.
“I am a huge believer in the power of compassion. I always try and bring it into a situation where I am angry to calm things down. Many FND episodes were triggered by high levels of anger that I was not able to voice. I found that if I could bring myself back to a compassion mindset then I could eventually dissolve the anger. This could mean compassion for myself and for others.”

BUTTERFLY HUG
Cross your arms, tap your chest alternately, and repeat soothing words to calm the nervous system
“I really enjoy the butterfly hug. It’s my way of showing kindness to myself and it really helps keep me calm.”
“It is one of the most simple things to do that helps regulate the nervous system (depending on arm capacity at that moment of course).”

COMPASSIONATE JOURNALING
Writing about difficult moments with a warm, understanding voice to cultivate self-support.
“I journal everyday. I always notice after hand writing about difficult days or moments. I feel a sense of relief afterwards.”
Final reflections

You may arrive here before you finish the book, skipping ahead to see what’s at the end, or you may have decided to go page by page and arrive here with all those pages already read or scanned. Wherever you are, and however you have chosen to engage with this book, I hope it has been a gentle, inspiring, supportive guide for your journey, for your nervous system and wellbeing, and that you feel less alone.

I want to say WELL DONE, well done for being who and how you are, for overcoming everything you have overcome, for your perseverance, and for keeping trust and hope alive despite all challenges and struggles.

Something I often share in my courses and 1:1 sessions is the importance, throughout recovery, of finding a balance between allowing ourselves to experience frustration, grief, discomfort, sadness, etc., and, once we allow these emotions to run through us, to really be and be expressed, remembering to gently bring our awareness and focus back to hope, to the things we can do, and to the beliefs that serve us, support us, and help us move forward. This is much easier said than done, but I wanted to share it with you here. It is not about blocking challenging emotions, escaping from them, or not feeling them, and it is not about being positive and hopeful all the time, but about finding a sweet balance between both.

Finally, I would like to share a couple of reflections from me to you, some of the things I share in my courses and 1:1 sessions, and some things I have learned from you, that have not been collected in the book.

Mindfully choose kind, understanding, helpful, and supportive inner dialogue. How we talk to ourselves, and what we feed our minds with, can affect how we feel and how we are. It makes sense, then, to be mindful of our narratives, beliefs, and inner dialogues, consciously choosing the ones that serve us, and, with care and kindness, saying bye-bye to those that no longer do (by saying bye, I mean bringing awareness when they arrive in your mind/heart and actively choose to not entertain them as you used to, and move your attention back to what you choose to nourish).


Which beliefs, narratives, or thoughts do you choose to cultivate?

Mornings are sweet moments to promote particular mindsets and intentions. Personally, I try to use my mind and body mindfully in the morning. For that, I use tools such as gratitude, setting a day's intention, positive affirmations, deep breathing, tapping, movement, and hydration (amongst others) in the first moments of my day. This helps me greatly to promote states of presence, acceptance, regulation, harmony, and readiness for whatever comes.

What small morning practices help you feel more present, regulated, and ready for whatever comes?

Once, I was asked how I use my toolkit, and I found myself saying that, for me, when I feel dysregulated, unwell, or uncomfortable with a particular emotion such as sadness, anger, frustration, etc. I try to remind myself that it is okay to feel what I am feeling (I find this difficult, as I often want to move out of that state as soon as possible). However, noticing what I am feeling, (“I notice…”), can help me create some distance (as I engage with the observing self) and feel less overwhelmed by it. Secondly, I mentally scan my toolkit for a technique that has helped me in the past, one of those “here & then” techniques that often immediately alleviate how I feel and helps me move towards regulation, such as 4-7-8 breathing, moving or tapping, listening to music, humming, etc. This is what we could call the “intervention” moment.

And then we also have the “promotion and prevention” moments. As I often say in my sessions, I warmly invite you to also bring attention to, and proactively use, your toolkit for promotion and prevention. By this, I mean: do not wait until you are feeling unwell to practice your techniques and tools. Use them as well to promote wellbeing and nervous system regulation, and to prevent dysregulation and flare up of symptoms. In other words, try to embed the techniques that help you into your day-to-day routine when you are feeling stable, grounded, and well. This can support your nervous system, create more space within, increase your window of tolerance, and help you feel more grounded and in control.

On another note, it is worth remembering the powerful role that community plays in regulation and well-being. Remember to keep talking, sharing, and seeking spaces where you can connect with others who are going through similar experiences and challenges. Look for interactions grounded in listening, presence, and mutual witnessing. Spaces where you can support one another in moving toward hope and regaining control and ease. 
 
Finally, there is a beautiful concept and tool called glimmers. Glimmers are those micro moments in the day that bring a sense of harmony, peace, and regulation within. This might be feeling the warmth of the sun on your skin, the sound of rain against the window, the smell of tea, etc. They can also be described as the opposite of triggers, the stimulus that brings us back to regulation. With this, I would like to invite you to be on the lookout for glimmers in your life. They are your allies for regulation. The more we bring our attention to what is present in the moment, the easier it can become to find glimmers around us. 
Is there any glimmer around you, ready to be discovered?


You’ve got this, darling. Even when it feels like everything is falling apart, when things feel dark like a rainy, cloudy winter day, the flowers are still making their way through, effortlessly. 

You are held.

And I would like to finish with an affirmation I say to myself very often:

 “I am healing and I am healed.”

With love,
 Irene 💛

